I've been printing since early 2014 and loving it! I run Mac and have tried most slicing software’s and settled with Simplify3D... although it costs there is no comparison. As for the machine I started with the XYZ DaVinci which was terrible compared to my FlashForge Creator Pro. My new machine is basically a rip-off of the Makerbot, but runs all materials and is much cheaper with the same reliability.

My design work is fairly simple/limited so I just use Tinkercad.com, but suits my needs. I love sharing with other enthusiasts or new comers so feel free to send me a message.

The ever concerning bed issues that we all encountered while learning were overcome by getting a piece of glass cut to fit my build plate, then printing some brackets to hold it and adjusting the Z axis by 5mm to allow for the glass. I now am able to run PLA on one side and leave the blue tape in place and ABS on the other side leaving the Kapton tape on.
I use subtractive making primarily, but just like making custom stuff.

I am a materials scientist working as the Principal Scientist for PANalytical, a leading developer of X-ray analysis instruments. In addition to using my 3D printer to create customized sample holders for our instruments, I am developing techniques for the analysis of 3D printed filaments and 3D printed parts. Techniques that I am exploring include X-ray diffraction analysis of partially crystalline thermoplastics such as POM and nylon; X-ray fluorescence spectrometry to determine the chemical purity of filaments and the consistency of pigment additives; and computed tomography (CT) to measure the precision of internal features in 3D printed parts and to produce computer models from original pieces to use as the basis for printing reproduction pieces.
